## Learning Objectives

### Computational Thinking Concepts (CT Concepts)

Based on [Harvard's CT Framework](https://scratched.gse.harvard.edu/ct/defining.html):

| Concept | Definition | Mastery Level by End of Course |
|---------|------------|-------------------------------|
| **Sequence** | Identifying a series of steps for a task | Apply independently in complex projects |
| **Events** | One thing causing another thing to happen | Use multiple event types purposefully |
| **Loops** | Running the same sequence multiple times | Choose appropriate loop type for context |
| **Conditionals** | Making decisions based on conditions | Implement nested and compound conditions |
| **Parallelism** | Making things happen at the same time | Coordinate multiple sprites effectively |
| **Operators** | Mathematical and logical expressions | Combine operators for complex logic |
| **Variables** | Storing, retrieving, and updating data | Use variables strategically for game states |

### Computational Thinking Practices (CT Practices)

| Practice | Definition | Development Across Sessions |
|----------|------------|----------------------------|
| **Experimenting & Iterating** | Developing through trial and error | Sessions 1-4 (introduce), 5-19 (develop), 20-24 (apply) |
| **Testing & Debugging** | Finding and fixing errors | Sessions 5-6 (introduce), 7-10 (develop), all subsequent (apply) |
| **Reusing & Remixing** | Building on existing work | Sessions 18-19 (focus), 20-24 (apply) |
| **Abstracting & Modularising** | Breaking into manageable parts | Sessions 13-15 (introduce), 20-24 (apply) |

### Computational Thinking Perspectives (CT Perspectives)

| Perspective | Indicator | Assessment Method |
|-------------|-----------|-------------------|
| **Expressing** | "I can create" | Project complexity and originality |
| **Connecting** | "I can collaborate" | Peer feedback quality, remix attribution |
| **Questioning** | "I can inquire" | Questions asked, problem-solving approaches |

