# MODULE 3: DATA & COORDINATION
## Sessions 11-15 | Focus: Variables, Parallelism

---

### Session 11: Introduction to Variables

**Duration:** 45 minutes

**Learning Objectives:**
- Understand what variables are and why we use them
- Create and name variables in Scratch
- Set and change variable values

**CT Concepts:** Variables (Data), Events
**CT Practices:** Experimenting and iterating
**21CC Focus:** Critical and Inventive Thinking

**Session Flow:**

| Time | Phase | Activity | Description |
|------|-------|----------|-------------|
| 0-5 min | Hook | Scoreboard Discussion | "How do games remember your score?" Show examples of game scores, timers, lives |
| 5-12 min | Unplugged | Human Variable | Student holds whiteboard = variable. Teacher says "set score to 0", student writes 0. "Change score by 10", student calculates and writes 10. Continue exercise |
| 12-18 min | Introduce | Variables in Scratch | Demonstrate creating variable, setting value, changing value, showing/hiding on stage |
| 18-30 min | Create | Click Counter | Guided: Sprite that counts clicks. Set score to 0 when flag clicked. When sprite clicked, change score by 1 |
| 30-40 min | Expand | Multiple Variables | Add second variable: "clicks needed" or "time" |
| 40-45 min | Reflect | Variable Uses | Brainstorm: What else could we store in variables? |

**Key Concepts:**
- Variable as named storage
- Set (assign value)
- Change by (add/subtract)
- Show/hide variable display

**Key Vocabulary:**
- Variable, Value
- Set, Change
- Data

**Mathematical Connection:**
- Addition and subtraction
- Keeping track/counting

**Assessment:**
- Variable created with sensible name
- Set and change used correctly
- Can explain what variable stores

**Take-home Challenge:**
- Make a project that uses a variable creatively

---

### Session 12: Variables - Scores, Timers, and Game States

**Duration:** 45 minutes

**Learning Objectives:**
- Implement scoring systems in games
- Create countdown timers
- Use variables to track game states

**CT Concepts:** Variables, Conditionals, Loops
**CT Practices:** Testing and debugging
**21CC Focus:** Critical and Inventive Thinking

**Session Flow:**

| Time | Phase | Activity | Description |
|------|-------|----------|-------------|
| 0-5 min | Review | Variable Recap | Quick review: set vs change, when to use each |
| 5-15 min | Timer Demo | Countdown Timer | Build together: Timer variable starts at 30, forever loop decreases by 1 every second, stops at 0 |
| 15-28 min | Enhance | Add Timer to Maze | Return to maze game; add score (for collectibles) and timer (countdown) |
| 28-38 min | Game State | Win/Lose with Variables | Use variables: lives, level, game over state |
| 38-43 min | Debug | Common Variable Bugs | Review common issues: forgetting to reset, wrong timing |
| 43-45 min | Reflect | Variable Power | "How do variables make our games better?" |

**Key Concepts:**
- Timer implementation
- Score systems
- Game state variables
- Variable conditions in if statements

**Common Variable Bugs:**
- Forgetting to initialize (set to 0 at start)
- Changing when should set, or vice versa
- Variable not visible when needed

**Assessment:**
- Timer counts down correctly
- Score increases appropriately
- Variables reset on new game

---

### Session 13: Introduction to Parallelism

**Duration:** 45 minutes

**Learning Objectives:**
- Understand that multiple scripts can run simultaneously
- Create projects with multiple sprites
- Each sprite has independent behaviour

**CT Concepts:** Parallelism, Events, Loops
**CT Practices:** Abstracting and modularising
**21CC Focus:** Critical and Inventive Thinking

**Session Flow:**

| Time | Phase | Activity | Description |
|------|-------|----------|-------------|
| 0-5 min | Hook | Game Analysis | Watch simple game video: How many things are happening at once? (player moves, enemy moves, score updates, music plays) |
| 5-12 min | Concept | Parallel vs Sequential | Demonstrate: Two sprites, each with own scripts started by green flag. Both run at same time! |
| 12-25 min | Create | Ocean Scene | Multiple sprites (fish, crab, bubble), each with own forever loop for movement. All run simultaneously |
| 25-38 min | Enhance | Independent Behaviours | Each sprite: different speed, different pattern, responds to different events |
| 38-43 min | Experiment | Add More Sprites | Students add sprites with independent behaviours |
| 43-45 min | Reflect | Parallelism Power | "Why is running things at the same time useful?" |

**Key Concepts:**
- Multiple scripts running simultaneously
- Each sprite has own scripts
- Green flag starts all relevant scripts

**Visualization:**
- Draw parallel timelines showing scripts running at same time

**Assessment:**
- Multiple sprites with independent behaviours
- Understanding that scripts run concurrently

---

### Session 14: Parallelism - Communication Between Sprites

**Duration:** 45 minutes

**Learning Objectives:**
- Use broadcast messages to communicate between sprites
- Coordinate sprite actions using broadcasts
- Create cause-and-effect relationships between sprites

**CT Concepts:** Parallelism, Events
**CT Practices:** Abstracting and modularising
**21CC Focus:** Critical and Inventive Thinking

**Session Flow:**

| Time | Phase | Activity | Description |
|------|-------|----------|-------------|
| 0-5 min | Problem | Coordination Challenge | "How can sprites talk to each other?" Demo: Sprite A should trigger action in Sprite B |
| 5-12 min | Introduce | Broadcast & Receive | Demonstrate broadcast "message", when I receive "message". Multiple sprites can receive same message |
| 12-25 min | Create | Chain Reaction | Guided: Click Sprite A → broadcasts "start" → Sprite B moves → broadcasts "next" → Sprite C appears → etc. |
| 25-35 min | Apply | Conversation Story | Two sprites have conversation using broadcasts to take turns |
| 35-42 min | Experiment | Complex Coordination | Add timing, multiple message types |
| 42-45 min | Reflect | When to Use Broadcast | "When is broadcast useful vs just using events?" |

**Key Concepts:**
- Broadcast (send message)
- When I receive (listen for message)
- Message naming conventions
- One-to-many communication

**Assessment:**
- Broadcasts used correctly
- Multi-sprite coordination works
- Can explain broadcast flow

